<span id="xv.iv.iv.xliii-p1"></span> <span class="c4"><span
id="xv.iv.iv.xliii-p1.1"></span>Canon XLII.  (Greek xiv.)</span>

<span id="xv.iv.iv.xliii-p2"></span>Concerning the not having feasts
under any circumstances in churches.

<span id="xv.iv.iv.xliii-p3"></span><span class="sc"><span
id="xv.iv.iv.xliii-p3.1"></span>That</span> no bishops or clerics are to
hold feasts in churches, unless perchance they are forced thereto by the
necessity of hospitality as they pass by.  The people, too, as far as
possible, are to be prohibited from attending such feasts.

<span id="xv.iv.iv.xliii-p4"></span><span class="c4"><span
id="xv.iv.iv.xliii-p4.1"></span>Notes.</span>

<span id="xv.iv.iv.xliii-p5"></span><span class="sc"><span
id="xv.iv.iv.xliii-p5.1"></span>Ancient Epitome of Canon XLII.</span>

<span id="xv.iv.iv.xliii-p6"></span>A cleric is not to feast in a
church, unless perchance he is driven thereto by the necessity of
hospitality.  This also is forbidden to the laity.

<span id="xv.iv.iv.xliii-p7"></span>This canon is Canon xxix. of the
Synod of Hippo, <span class="sc"><span
id="xv.iv.iv.xliii-p7.1"></span>a.d.</span> 393.

